(42, 20, 18, 27, 2, 34, 35, 'that stone shall be broken', 'Connection of the Stone Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the destructive power of the stone. In Luke, the stone causes brokenness or destruction, while in Daniel, it smashes the image and becomes a great mountain, symbolizing ultimate authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 18, 27, 2, 44, 45, 'that stone shall be broken', 'Connection of the Stone Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the destructive power of the stone. In Luke, the stone causes brokenness or destruction, while in Daniel, the stone breaks and consumes other kingdoms. This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment and the establishment of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 18, 38, 12, 3, 3, 'that stone shall be broken', 'Connection of Burdensome Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the destructive nature of the stone. In Luke, falling on the stone results in being broken, while Zechariah describes those who burden themselves with the stone being cut in pieces.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 18, 40, 21, 44, 44, NULL, 'Connection of Stone Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of falling on the stone, highlighting the theme of brokenness and destruction. The identical phrasing reinforces the significance of the stone in both contexts.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 18, 40, 21, 34, 34, NULL, 'Judgment and Accountability Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of rejecting God''s message. The ''fruit'' in Matthew represents the expected response to God''s servants, while the ''stone'' in Luke symbolizes the judgment faced by those who oppose it.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 18, 52, 2, 16, 16, 'shall be broken', 'Judgment and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment in both passages. Luke 20:18 speaks of being broken or ground to powder, while 1 Thessalonians 2:16 refers to the wrath coming upon those who oppose salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 19, 42, 19, 47, 48, NULL, 'Opposition from Religious Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility of the chief priests and scribes towards Jesus. In Luke 19:47-48, they seek to destroy him, while in Luke 20:19, they actively plot against him after perceiving his parable as a direct challenge.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 19, 40, 21, 45, 46, 'sought to lay hands on him', 'Connection of Chief Priests'' Reactions', 'Both passages emphasize the chief priests'' realization that Jesus spoke against them and their fear of the people. This connection highlights their desire to lay hands on him due to the perceived threat he posed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 19, 40, 26, 3, 4, 'sought to lay hands on him', 'Plot Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of the chief priests and scribes conspiring against Jesus. In Luke, they seek to lay hands on him, while in Matthew, they consult to kill him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 19, 41, 12, 12, 12, 'sought to lay hands on him', 'Connection of Rejection by Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the leaders'' intent to lay hands on Jesus due to their recognition that he spoke a parable against them. This shared theme illustrates their fear of the people''s reaction, highlighting their awareness of the implications of Jesus'' words.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 19, 42, 20, 14, 14, NULL, 'Rejection of the Heir', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of the heir, with the husbandmen plotting to kill him in Luke 20:14, and the chief priests and scribes recognizing that Jesus'' parable speaks against them in Luke 20:19. This connection highlights the theme of opposition to God''s messengers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 20, 42, 11, 54, 54, NULL, 'Plot Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of those who sought to entrap Jesus through deceitful means. They highlight the intent to catch him in his words for the purpose of accusation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 20, 40, 22, 15, 22, 'take hold of his words', 'Entanglement in Speech', 'Both passages emphasize the attempts to entrap Jesus through deceitful questioning. In Luke, the spies are sent to take hold of his words, while in Matthew, the Pharisees and Herodians seek to entangle him in his talk.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 20, 19, 81, 15, 15, NULL, 'Opposition to God''s Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of opposition to God''s authority. In Luke, the spies seek to undermine Jesus, while in Psalms, the haters of the Lord are called to submit to Him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 20, 24, 11, 19, 19, NULL, 'Plot Against the Innocent', 'This connection highlights the schemes against the innocent. Both passages emphasize the plotting of unjust individuals against those who are unaware of their intentions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 20, 40, 27, 2, 2, 'deliver him unto the power and authority', 'Connection of Betrayal and Authority', 'This connection highlights the act of delivering Jesus to authority. In Luke, the spies aim to deliver him to the governor, while Matthew describes Jesus being led to Pontius Pilate, the governor.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 20, 23, 29, 20, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Watching for Iniquity', 'Both passages emphasize the act of watching for wrongdoing and laying traps for the just. In Luke, the spies seek to take hold of Jesus'' words, while Isaiah speaks of those who watch for iniquity and make a man an offender for a word.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 20, 41, 12, 13, 17, 'take hold of his words', 'Plot Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the attempts to catch Jesus in his words. In Luke, spies are sent to take hold of his words, while in Mark, Pharisees and Herodians are sent to catch him in his words.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 21, 40, 22, 16, 16, 'teachest the way of God truly', 'Connection of Teaching Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus'' truthful teaching and impartiality. They highlight that he teaches the way of God without favoritism, showcasing a consistent portrayal of his authority.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 21, 40, 26, 49, 50, 'Master, we know that thou sayest', 'Recognition of Authority', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus'' authority in both passages. In Luke, the questioners recognize Jesus as a true teacher, while in Matthew, Judas addresses Jesus as ''master,'' indicating a similar recognition before betrayal.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 21, 52, 2, 4, 5, 'teachest the way of God truly', 'Integrity in Teaching', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on teaching truthfully without seeking to please men. Both passages stress the importance of sincerity and integrity in conveying God''s message.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 21, 47, 2, 17, 17, 'teachest the way of God truly', 'Integrity in Teaching', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on sincerity and truth in teaching. Both passages stress the importance of teaching the way of God truly and not corrupting the word of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 21, 14, 19, 7, 7, NULL, 'Respect of Persons', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of not showing favoritism. Luke 20:21 highlights Jesus'' impartial teaching, while 2 Chronicles 19:7 explicitly states there is no respect of persons with God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 21, 18, 34, 19, 19, 'acceptest thou the person of any', 'Divine Impartiality Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of impartiality in both passages. Luke 20:21 emphasizes teaching without favoritism, while Job 34:19 states that God does not regard the rich more than the poor.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 21, 19, 12, 2, 2, 'teachest the way of God truly', 'Flattery and True Teaching', 'This connection highlights the contrast between true teaching and insincere speech. Luke 20:21 emphasizes teaching the way of God truly, while Psalms 12:2 critiques those who speak with flattering lips and a double heart.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 22, 16, 9, 37, 37, 'tribute unto Cesar', 'Tribute and Dominion Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority and subjugation. Both passages emphasize the burden of tribute and the dominion of rulers over the people, reflecting their distress under foreign powers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 22, 5, 17, 15, 15, 'Is it lawful for us to give tribute', 'Authority and Governance', 'This connection highlights the theme of lawful authority in governance. Luke 20:22 questions the legitimacy of tribute to Caesar, while Deuteronomy 17:15 establishes God''s choice in leadership.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 22, 15, 4, 13, 13, 'tribute', 'Tribute and Authority Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of tribute and its implications for authority. Luke 20:22 questions the lawfulness of paying tribute to Caesar, while Ezra 4:13 warns that not paying tribute could harm the king''s revenue.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 22, 15, 4, 19, 22, 'tribute unto Cesar', 'Tribute and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of tribute and authority in both passages. Luke 20:22 questions the lawfulness of paying tribute to Caesar, while Ezra 4:19-22 discusses the historical context of tribute paid to kings, emphasizing the importance of allegiance to governing authorities.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 22, 16, 5, 4, 4, 'tribute', 'Tribute and Authority Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of tribute, questioning its legitimacy and necessity. In Luke, the inquiry about tribute to Caesar parallels the mention of borrowing for the king''s tribute in Nehemiah.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
